rtd to computer via usart and microcontroller using c++ and was about to do assembly, before I moved on. I actually haven't done embedded since 2018, but I want to start getting back into into it. I had no programming background and just googled, read, and copy/pasted from stack exchange.

>I got a bit into it but most websites and the like seem to think I know what most tools and commands allow you to do instead of teaching you the deconstruction of the functions or working as a "tutorial" for them.

It depends on what your trying to learn. No matter what if your doing this on your own, your going to spend a lot of time researching things. You might have to eventually decide if what your goal is too learn a language/style of programing/OS or a app/controller. For the former, deconstructions of functions should be easier found, but they would be mainly in academic /college books($$$) that specify the libraries and setup required to do these functions in their context. You can pirate a lot of these books from lib gen. If your doing the latter like I did, then it helps to get some kind of compiler or something as soon as possible so you can do trial and error to meander past all the BS. For example, I didn't need to worry about file streams (yet) and the such for c++ as they were showing in the books, rather I just needed to look at the micro controller-manual, stack-exchange, and interrupts.

In all I highly recommend you search lib gen for books about coding. Just download a bunch of books on the same topic and you will eventually find one that is talking like a normal person. Plus it helps to compare/contrast the illustration of concepts in 5+ books, it helps you understand it. It help me learned about van larr constants. No matter what in the end I have gain powerful tools in /hmofa/ comfy omptization

Sorry if that was a ramble and did not make sense.
